 ## Expected Smoke-Test Behavior
 
-When `CONFIG_CLAWCAM_CAMERA_SMOKE_TEST_ON_BOOT=y`, the firmware should initialize the ESP32-S3-EYE camera pin map, attempt one JPEG capture, log the captured frame length and dimensions, and release the framebuffer. If `CONFIG_CLAWCAM_STORAGE_PERSIST_SMOKE_TEST_CAPTURE=y`, a successful capture is also written to `/sdcard/media`, paired smoke-test metadata is written to `/sdcard/metadata`, and a gateway-ingestible `clawcam.event.v1`-shape event artifact is written to `/sdcard/events`. If `CONFIG_CLAWCAM_GATEWAY_UPLOAD_ENABLED=y`, the firmware also attempts to register the bench node and POST the generated event JSON to the gateway API. SD-card artifacts remain the offline source of truth; upload failure is logged but does not delete or alter local artifacts. If the camera, storage, or gateway client path is disabled or unavailable, the firmware logs the failure and uses `ESP_ERR_NOT_SUPPORTED` or a concrete ESP-IDF error rather than pretending success.
+When `CONFIG_CLAWCAM_CAMERA_SMOKE_TEST_ON_BOOT=y`, the firmware should initialize the ESP32-S3-EYE camera pin map, attempt one JPEG capture, log the captured frame length and dimensions, and release the framebuffer. If `CONFIG_CLAWCAM_STORAGE_PERSIST_SMOKE_TEST_CAPTURE=y`, a successful capture is also written to `/sdcard/media`, paired smoke-test metadata is written to `/sdcard/metadata`, and a gateway-ingestible `clawcam.event.v1`-shape event artifact is written to `/sdcard/events`. If `CONFIG_CLAWCAM_GATEWAY_UPLOAD_ENABLED=y`, the firmware also attempts to register the bench node and POST the generated event JSON to the gateway API. The gateway upload is preceded by a call into the `clawcam_wifi_manager`; when `CONFIG_CLAWCAM_WIFI_ENABLED=y` and STA credentials are provided, the manager blocks up to `CONFIG_CLAWCAM_WIFI_CONNECT_TIMEOUT_MS` and retries up to `CONFIG_CLAWCAM_WIFI_MAX_RETRIES` times before failing. SD-card artifacts remain the offline source of truth; Wi-Fi failure, upload failure, or disabled Wi-Fi is logged but does not delete or alter local artifacts. If the camera, storage, Wi-Fi, or gateway client path is disabled or unavailable, the firmware logs the failure and uses `ESP_ERR_NOT_SUPPORTED` or a concrete ESP-IDF error rather than pretending success.
 
